            <fr:title text="Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral is a generalization of the Riemann integral that allows for the integration of a broader class of functions. It is defined for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0057.xml" addr="FA-0057" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link> on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The construction of the Lebesgue integral proceeds in several steps:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>First, define the integral for non-negative <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0060.xml" addr="FA-0060" title="Simple function">simple functions</fr:link> (finite linear combinations of indicator functions of measurable sets).</fr:li>
<fr:li>Then, extend this definition to non-negative measurable functions using monotone approximation by simple functions.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Finally, define the integral for general measurable functions by separately integrating their positive and negative parts.</fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral has many advantages over the Riemann integral:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>It allows for the integration of a larger class of functions</fr:li>
<fr:li>It has better convergence properties, exemplified by the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0051.xml" addr="FA-0051" title="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:link> and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0050.xml" addr="FA-0050" title="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>It provides a more natural setting for limiting operations and for the study of function spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
